<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
ROFL, Crank.  Ok, here's my take, which will be at variance with many of the ranters here:<P>The price increase isn't that bad.  Nothing else has stayed the same price for three years.  Especially not programmer and network engineer compensation.  Crank this into your calculations: EQ does not run on that $799 Best Buy special sitting on your desk.  Every "server" is actually approximately 27 networked computers.  Not cheap, best-bang-for-the-buck boxes like you or I use, but heavy-duty, high volume $10,000 and <I>up</I> servers.  27 x 45= <B>1,215</B> machines.  (note, we are not even getting into hubs, switches, cabling, racks, physical space, UPS...this is why its called a "server farm.") Of that number, how many will need replacing in any given month?  Generally, a computer is totally obsolete in 3 years.  So average 1/3 of the servers: or <B>405</B> new computers/year just to run the game.  There's a cool $4 mill and we haven't even gotten into the desktop systems used by the 50-odd programmers and content developers, then the GM's, etc.<P>Now it's also obvious that they're repositioning their price structure to be in line with the other MMORPG's, which I do object to, because that's price fixing.  <P>And I also sent to the Developer's Corner a word or two about the Bazaar and UI. We <B>do</B> deserve an update on those, considering a price increase and new expansion have been announced.
</FONT>
