<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Look, the real issue here isn't whether the price increase is warranted or not, or whether it's to much or to little.  Rather, the issue to me is that SOE and Verant continue to charge for services they promise, but consistantly fail to deliver in a reasonable and/or timely manner.  It has now been over 3 months since the release of Luclin and aside from the new graphics engine, the other main selling features of the expansion(bazaar, new UI) are still undelivered and they do not even have an estimate of when they will be completed.  What is the most frustrating to me is that instead of commiting their entire team to fixing the current problems and delivering what they have PROMISED and I have ALREADY PAID FOR, they stick a small team to work on it in their spare time while the rest of the staff hastily throws together new expansions ,that like the last one, will be buggy and incomplete when released leaving us frustrated once again.  <P>SOE and Verant like to compare their product to other forms of entertainment like going to the movies.  Lets really look at that analogy a little closer.  If SOE and Verant ran a movie theatre, this is how your movie experience would be:  First, you would have to buy a movie pass for $40 that would allow you to go to the theatre and watch movies, in addition, there would be a $12 monthly fee to cover "operating expenses" and "new movies".  However, when a highly anticipated new feature film is released, you will be charged an additional $30 to be able to watch it, but this only happens about once a year.  After you have recieved your movie pass, you walk in to a theatre that is packed.  There is hardly any room to sit.  You finally find a seat and the show begins.  For some reason the movie plays as if in slow motion, stopping altogether at times.  The soundtrack is erratic and for some reason all you can hear is footsteps.  About half way through the movie, right at a climatic scene, it suddenly goes black and all you can see on the screen are the words "YOU HAVE BEEN DISCONNECTED".  The next thing you  know you find yourself standing in the parking lot butt naked.  You spend the next 30 minutes trying to get back in the theatre, but all the doors are locked.  Eventually, you get back in and try to track down a manager to find out where your clothes are and what the heck is going on.  You notice on the door to the managers office a sign that says his office hours are from 8:00am to 10:00pm monday thru friday.  Looking at your watch you notice its 6:00pm on friday but no one is in the office.  You wander around for the next 5 hours looking for the manager before finally an employee shows up to help.  However, come to find out, the employee, although very friendly, is just a volunteer and has no authority to help you recover your clothes.  He also has no idea how you ended up in the parking lot either.  Finally, you find your clothes with the help of some friends and head off to watch the new feature film you've paid $30 for.  After the movie starts 45 minutes late, you begin to watch the film, fascinated by the new dazzling special effects.  Suddenly, half way through the film, the screen once again goes black.  Almost immediately, you hear a voice come over the intercom announcing that they haven't actually finished filming the movie yet and they are unsure when it will be completed.  You sit there in disbelief for a moment when suddenly, the screen flares back on.  This time however, it is not the second half of the movie, but rather a preview for the upcoming sequel that you can purchase your pass to shortly for another $30.<P>The real sad part is that we will continue to buy expansions and pay the monthly fee for a shoddy product simply because there is nothing better out there.  <P>Tralik Windwielder<BR>51 Pathfinder
</FONT>
