<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
*gathers thoughts together*<P>I apologize now for the long post....<P><BR>I have played the game since as far back as it existed.  I have seen the world of Norrath change hundreds of times over the years.  I have seen some friendships made and many more destroyed.  I have seen loot tear asunder the guilds and friends as the game progresses.<P>In the beginning, it was Norrath, the Old World if you will.  There was much rejoicing in the lands and people came far and wide to play the game.  In time, many reached the level limits of 50th and explored all there was to explore.  classes came into being, like enchanters, that had no real power in the beginning and grew to enormous power.  There were many changes to the game made.  A great many pondered the future of Norrath then.<P>In the wisdom, Kurnark was born.  The people once more rejoiced.  The lands were rushed upon and devoured by the eager people.  The riches and spoils went to those that could find them first.  Secrets were kept as long as possible until the word got out and "BLAM" the loot flooded the markets once more.  All "Old World" stuff became as commonplace as the combine weapons we all fought to buy in the start of the game.  Or perhaps the Runed Totem staves?  In time, all of the "problems" of the "Old World" was forgotten and put aside.<P>In time, the money began to slow.  People flocked to the new games on the market, AO, DAoC and etc.  Many felt this was because of the quality of the games.  Not necessarily the "same genre" of game platform.  In time, some of these same people (even myself) for a time tried these new games.  But in the end, Everquest reigned supreme compared to the rest of the competitors.  Hence, we flocked once more to our beloved world of Norrath.  The other games continued to survive as there are many that feel Sony/VI screwed them over or they had had enough of the poor customer service.<P>Then came Velious.  We hardly had time to really enjoy velious at all and then Shadows of Luclin appeared.<P>Just when things came to head, the Shadows of Luclin were casted across the people of Norrath and the problems once more became just memories to hash on behind the scenes.  SoL made promises beyond compare.  ALL of us raced out, not only to buy the game, but to buy NEW hardware.  For it seemed that the world of Norrath, our beloved world, required even MORE from us.  New hardware.  It wasn't $30 to upgrade to Shadows of Luclin for some, it was $1000-2000.00 for each player to upgrade to handle the engine for Shadows of Luclin.  Many of Norrath once more rejoiced at the beauty and splendor of Shadows of Luclin (myself included).  Again, problems were forgotten or backshelved once more in lieu of a new platform.<P>Then, we all find out about "Legends" and now "Planes of Power".<P><BR>Here is some things to consider, from an old fossil -<P>1.) People leave guilds and friends over loot 85% of the time.  Loot changes wind as fast as the expansions come out.  This is because the expansions MUST be more/better than the prior.  Hence, if people were to stop and think on it - "All of those you fought over to get that one item was pointless because in 9-12 months, a new expansion will be released obsoleting it."   Expansions are NOT just released for the players to have MORE to do, but they are required to drive the "economy" of the game.  To keep the game from stagnating on itself.  Perhaps instead of new expansions, look at ways of improving the game economy.<P>2.) I know I can feel lied to at times from Sony/VI when articles appear saying/quoting, "We currently aren't working on something else, etc etc" and then a month or two later, we find out that you HAD INDEED started something different.  You lied many times on this, and many of us have witnessed it.  Some have stepped forward and spoken out.  Me, I chose to bite my lip and be disappointed.  Foresight is hindsight.  Why do we need MORE EXPANSIONS, Planes of Power for example, WHEN you haven't finished pieces of "Old World", Kurnark, Velious, and Shadows of Luclin?   I mean 3 years, 36 months, you have had 3 major upgrades/expansions.  This does not include ALL the free content.  You are releasing expansions at a minimum of every 9 months.  This means that ALL the bugs are going to be fixed in 9 months WHILE you are writing new code?  I don't buy it.  I think many others don't either.  We ALL know that you feel the only way to rake in the money is to get new content out the door so players have "something" to do.  I just feel that Sony/VI lies to us a lot of the time.  You make us think your fixing the problems, but then turn around and announce new products/services.   I will admit, $10 a month is not a lot to pay, but when there are 400,000+ subscribers a month, that is a lot of money involved. People do notice.<P>3.) There are many promises that have been made over the years, and many of the them have been kept.  We, the players, salute you for this.  However, there have been many promises unkept as well over the years.  We the players wonder HOW/WHEN your going to fix these, when you obviously have other products/services in production?  When are the balancing issues for example going to be done, if your staff is split across multiple services?  You can't keep doing this.  It will bite you in the ass as newer games ARE coming.  You ALREADY know that about half, if not more, of your user base is going to try Star Wars Galaxies.   Many are going to be doing Shadowbane, City of Heroes and World of Warcraft as well.  You have a lot of competition ahead.  If you want to win your customers, win them through your actions.  Customer Service/Tech Support seems to be a major issue.  As I have told others in my life - "If you are not part of the solution, then you are part of the problem."  Take the time now to improve Customer Service/Tech Support.  I will glady pay you your 30% increase for that one item alone.  You lose people because it seems you don't really care about them.  Hence, the "vision" you have, is different than the "vision" we hold.<P>4.) Get out among the players, talk to them more.  Find out what is REALLY going on out there.  Many feel unwanted, unnoticed.  The Legends thing, while be a great monetary factor, really put the rest of the community in a bad light.  It made it seem that - "You want the good stuff, you need to pay for it".   I thought I was already paying for the "good stuff" myself.  Was I wrong?<P>and on and on and on.....<P>In closing, I have played a very long time in Norrath (about 385 days played since retail).  I still have only seen maybe 75% of the old world, 50% Kurnark, 35% of Velious and 15% of Luclin.  I don't have time to enjoy anything new.  You are pushing me at the bit, when the truth is - "We as players, can't keep the pace you've set for us".   I'm tired of paying for more expansions, when I never really get to enjoy them fully.  I will pay your increase, only in hopes that you, as the "vision" will at least take some course of action to better the experience of Everquest for new and old players alike.  Not expansions, not new zones, but better customer service/tech support.  Better in-game support.  Better overall experiences in the game (GM quests and such).  The game has PLENTY of content.  Fix what you have already before the next game comes along and steals your customers....<P><BR>Lunamin Silvermoon<BR>Fossil of Fennin Ro
</FONT>
